\f0\b\fs42 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 2. How Parallax Math Works\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading80\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 To make the sky feel miles away, it needs to move incredibly slowly. While your guard walks left and right across the screen at 3 or 4 pixels per frame, the sky should slowly slide in 
\f2\b \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 one direction
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774  at a fraction of a pixel per frame, matching the natural rotation of the earth over your 6-hour loop.\
Instead of cutting the image when it hits the edge, we use Python\'92s modulo (
\fs28\fsmilli14118 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 %
\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 ) math to loop the panorama seamlessly.\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\sa80\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs42 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 3. Python Implementation: The Parallax Sky Engine\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading80\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 Add this script logic directly into the top of your frame loop. It calculates the moving window position on the panoramic sky, crops out a 1920x1080 window, and places it at the very bottom of your visual layer stack.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading40\partightenfactor0

\f4\i\fs28\fsmilli14118 \AppleTypeServices \cf0 # --- OPTIMIZED PARALLAX SKY LOOP ENGINE ---
\f5\i0 \
\

\f4\i # Configuration settings for sky movement velocity
\f5\i0 \
SKY_PANORAMA_WIDTH = 3840\
STREAM_CANVAS_WIDTH = 1920\

\f4\i # Moves exactly 1 pixel every 5 frames (incredibly slow and relaxing drift)
\f5\i0 \
SKY_SPEED_FACTOR = 0.2 \
\
def render_parallax_sky(cycle_frame):\
    
\f4\i # Calculate the horizontal pixel shift based on the current timeline frame
\f5\i0 \
    
\f4\i # Modulo ensures that when the offset hits the end of the panorama, it loops back to 0
\f5\i0 \
    sky_offset_x = int(cycle_frame * SKY_SPEED_FACTOR) % (SKY_PANORAMA_WIDTH - STREAM_CANVAS_WIDTH)\
    \
    
\f4\i # Define the crop boundary box to cut out of our extra-wide sky panorama
\f5\i0 \
    
\f4\i # Crop coordinates: (Left, Upper, Right, Lower)
\f5\i0 \
    crop_box = (sky_offset_x, 0, sky_offset_x + STREAM_CANVAS_WIDTH, 1080)\
    \
    
\f4\i # Extract the visible 1920x1080 sky window for this exact frame
\f5\i0 \
    
\f4\i # Using open panoramic asset already cached in RAM outside the loop
\f5\i0 \
    visible_sky_frame = panoramic_sky.crop(crop_box)\
    \
    return visible_sky_frame\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading80\partightenfactor0

